President Donald J. Trump has announced his intent to nominate Mary Elizabeth Taylor as Assistant Secretary of State for Legislative Affairs. Taylor currently serves as a senior advisor in the Office of the Counselor of the Department of State and previously worked as Special Assistant to the President for Legislative Affairs at the White House. She has played a key role in guiding Senate nominations and successfully confirming over four hundred nominees, including Supreme Court Justice Neil Gorsuch, Secretary of State Michael Pompeo, and CIA Director Gina Haspel. Taylor has also worked in the office of United States Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, providing parliamentary advice and counsel on legislative matters. Aditya Bamzai and Travis LeBlanc have also been nominated to serve as Members of the Privacy and Civil Liberties Oversight Board. Bamzai's term would expire on January 29, 2020, while LeBlanc's term would expire on January 29, 2022.